Jerry's home page

Introduction ¶

The Study¶

While researching a topic for this capstone project, I came across an academic paper that influenced where millions of dollars of development funds will be used. The "Neighborhood Opportunity Fund" (NOF) in Chicago can award up to \$2.5 million for individual projects in "Qualified Investment Areas." Information on the program explained that the choice of geographic areas to receive the grants was influenced by the study "Mapping the DNA of Urban Neighborhoods: Clustering Longitudinal Sequences of Neighborhood Socioeconomic Change" by Elizabeth Delmelle. The study classified neighborhoods by socioeconomic, housing, and demographic variables using US census data from the years of 1970 to 2010, so that it could be used to identify areas in need of investment. Throughout this report I will refer to the study as "Dr. Delmelle's study," the "DNA of Urban Neighborhoods study," or the "2010 study." 2010 is the year of the latest data used in the study, not its publication date.

This project will try to repeat and extend this study with the latest census data (2019), then compare the new results to the locations of where some of the funds are going to be awarded. The objective will be to evaluate if the funds, given the updated information, are going to neighborhoods most in need of investment. The original study examined both Chicago and Los Angeles. This project will only address Chicago.

Replication¶

Years back I read the paper Why Most Published Research Findings Are False, by John P. A. Ioannidis, also described in Wikipedia. It raised the concerns that, even though replication is an essential part of science, few replications are attempted and even fewer are done successfully. Dr. Delmelle's study was very interesting, utilized much of the algorithms taught in the IBM online courses, and will influence the allocation of millions of dollars in taxpayer money. It's worth replicating it, to the extent possible, and updating it with the latest data available.

This project won't reproduce the exact the results of the previous study for a number of reasons:

  1. The original study starts off using K-means clustering, which is a technique sensitive to which initial values are chosen, therefore since initial values often are chosen at random, exact replication cannot be guaranteed.
  2. I will update the census data with 2019 data from the American Community Survey. So I'll be using a larger dataset.
  3. The previous study did not publish the exact data cleaning process or the classification of every single census tract, so a higher-level comparison will have to do.

Where the Money Is Going¶

An organization called INVEST South/West is in charge of allocating much of the NOF for parts of Chicago. They have an RFP page explaining how developers can solicit these funds for projects in predetermined locations. I manually transcribed the addresses of the RFPs into a CSV file and will be adding to that dataset using Python libraries throughout this study.

Data Sources¶

Longitudinal Tract Data Base (LTDB). This is the data used for the original study. It contains census data from 1970 to 2010. It is downloadable as zip files from an interactive menu from the web link given. The file names to download are LTDB_Std_All_fullcount.zip and LTDB_Std_All_Sample.zip.

American Community Survey Data (ACS). This will be from the five-year survey for 2019. It will be retrieved using the U.S. Census API via the Python library "censusdata"

Census shape files for tract geospatial information. These are zip files downloaded with a "curl" command. I use the Python library "GeoPanda" to convert the shape files in NAD83 coordinates to GeoJSON in WS84 coordinates. I found GeoJSON easier to work with during debugging, plus the Python library "Folium" defaults to WS84.

The original "Mapping the DNA of Urban Neighborhoods" study. Some tables are extracted from the PDF using the Python library "tabula."

RFP's to receive Neighborhood Opportunity Funds. Each RFP is eligible to receive from \$250,000 to $2.5 million dollars in funding. I had to manually transcribe the addresses from the RFP into a CSV and then use the Python library geopy to update the geospatial data to use it as input to the library Folium.

Methodology Overall ¶

The original study sketched out the following process that we will replicate:

We start out doing K-means clustering and later use hierarchical agglomerative clustering. Each of those steps deserved their own section so we will have more than one data and methodology section, since the narrative will make more sense if we keep the descriptions of the data cleaning close to how they are used.

In summary:

  • The K-means clustering classifications of the census tracts are lined up as a series, each year being one data item in the series. That series is input for the next step.
  • Difference for each tract series is calculated by the optimal matching distance algorithm (OMA). This creates a difference matrix which is input for the next step.
  • Based on the series difference, the census tracts are classified by hierarchical agglomerative clustering. This is our final classification.

K-means Clustering by Census Data ¶

Data: K-means¶

The data for the original study was obtained from the "Diversity and Disparities" project hosted at Brown University and can be downloaded from the link already given. The "DNA of Urban Neighborhoods" study gave a description of the variables used. From those descriptions I determined that they correspond to the variables shown below in the LTDB and ACS tables. All of the variables are percentages except for median home value. But the variables as percentages only exist in the LTDB for the most recent year, 2010. Previous years have to be calculated from variables in whole numbers. XX in variable names is replaced by the last 2 digits of the year being calculated. In the below table the LTDB column is the variables as percentages used for 2010, the column LTDB Formula are the variable names used to calculate percentages in earlier years, and the column Census Code is the ACS table used to calculate percentages for 2019. Census data for 2019 was collected using the US census department's API.

All data are defined on the census tract level. Census tracts are defined as small, relatively permanent statistical subdivisions of a county as part of the Census Bureau's Participant Statistical Areas Program. Census tracts generally have a population size between 1,200 and 8,000 people, with an optimum size of 4,000 people. A census tract usually covers a contiguous area.

I manually downloaded the files 'LTDB_Std_All_fullcount.zip' and 'LTDB_Std_All_Sample.zip' from the web site and programmatically unzipped them. The python functions I wrote looked in both sets of files for the variables but in the end only the 'Sample' files were used.

I did have a bit of trouble due to a typo in the LTDB documentation that said the variable ppovXX is calculated with a variable povXX. However, this should have been a variable named npovXX. I have to thank Professor John R. Logan of Brown University for quickly answering by email about this problem.

All the tables and variables available from the ACS are documented at this link to the U.S. Census page

Data: K-means: Data Cleaning¶

While processing the data I did notice some missing values and outliers. A few calculated values had the Python number for infinity, indicating there is data with zero in the total that I used as the denominator calculating a variable. I decided to use Tukey's fences method to define outliers: The definition from Wikipedia is:

Tukey's fences method flags observations based on measures such as the interquartile range. For example, if Q1 and Q3 are the lower and upper quartiles respectively, then one could define an outlier to be any observation outside the range:

Q1 − k(Q3 − Q1), Q3 + k(Q3 − Q1)

for some nonnegative constant k. John Tukey proposed this test, where k = 1.5 indicates an "outlier," and k = 3 indicates data that is "far out."

I used k=3 because I don't want to eliminate values that might indicate true large disparities between neighborhoods. When counting everything up I had very few bad data values, less than 1% for every year except 1980, which has a little over only 2% due to missing values.

1970 1980 1990 2000 2010 2019
NaN 41 309 1 2 0 0
Outlier 105 57 85 66 62 71
Percent bad 0.92% 2.32% 0.54% 0.43% 0.39% 0.45%

We can visualize the outliers for 1970, (the year with the most outliers) with a box plot:

Despite the fact that a small number of our data values are clearly errors, some of the less extreme outliers in the boxplot will remain when we choose k=3 with Tukey's method. This is appropriate since census tracts are not extremely large areas, therefore some unusually large values are possible, within reason.

Data: K-means: Standardization¶

As indicated in Dr. Delmelle's study I will transform the data to their Z-values for each variable for each year, to control for different measurement scales and to compare changes across time. In other words, since we are ranking census tracts against each other, we only care about relative values. For this I used StandardScaler() from the sklearn (scikit-learn) library.

Methodology: K-means¶

Since the number clusters were determined by the study I am replicating, I don't have to analyze runs with the "elbow method" to determine the best number of clusters. K-means is known to be sensitive to initial conditions so I ran the fit 9 times with random_state set to a different number each time, then saved the one with the lowest sum of squared distances to closest cluster center, as saved in the "inertia_" attribute. All these metrics were very close, so I don't think this step was critical to better performance.

My objective here is to pair up the clusters created with the updated data with the clusters of the previous study. Those clusters classified neighborhoods as:

  1. New Suburban
  2. Older, Stable Suburban
  3. Blue Collar
  4. Struggling
  5. Young Urban

The original study did not list a per-census-tract classification by K-means, but in the appendix there was a table that has the mean Z scores for each variable for each cluster. I extract this information to Python pandas from the PDF document using the library "tabula."

My first thought was I could just treat each column of mean Z scores for each cluster as a vector, calculate the Euclidean distance, and then pair them up based on the lowest value first. That did not work well at all. When I graphed the results, there was little similarity apparent. The original study did have an extreme value that my handling of outliers might have eliminated, which would make this method of pairing more difficult. The original study reported a mean Z-score of -8.84 for "% four-year degree" in the Struggling cluster. This is an unusual Z-score for any sample or data point.

Instead, what worked was a simple series of decisions, as follows:

  1. Find maximum for manufacturing employment, assign that to Blue Collar
  2. Find maximum for poverty of remaining clusters, assign that to Struggling
  3. Find minimum for structures over 30 years of remaining clusters, assign that to New Suburban
  4. Find minimum for people living at their residence less than 10 years of remaining clusters, assign that to Old Suburban
  5. Assign last cluster to Young Urban

Here we have the results of the pair up:

The Young Urban yellow areas are expanding over time into places that have been known to be gentrified. Intuitively, over time the New Suburban areas become Old Suburban areas, since all you have to do for that is wait and age.

Optimal Matching Distance Algorithm (OMA) ¶

By using the "DNA of Urban Neighborhoods" study, the NOF grants are considering not only the present state of a neighborhood but also its trajectory over time. This trend information is relevant because a struggling but gentrifying area may not need the funds as much as a blue collar neighborhood that is starting to struggle, and certainly areas stuck in a stable long time stagnation would need the most attention.

Data: Optimal Matching Distance Algorithm (OMA):¶

The input for the OMA must be a series, therefore each data row is one census tract with each classification for each year as a categorical variable from 1970 to 2019. The output is a dissimilarity matrix.

Methodology: Optimal Matching Distance Algorithm (OMA):¶

Dr. Delmelle explains the algorithm: <<" the algorithm assesses the cost of inserting, deleting, or substituting elements in one sequence to completely transform it into another sequence; the more steps needed to make two sequences equal, the greater the cost or dissimilarity between the two.">> ... <<"Substitution costs resulting from transition rates are calculated as follows:

$2-p(i \mid j) - p(j \mid i)$

where $p(i \mid j)$ is the transition rate or probability of observing a transition between socioeconomic class from time $t$ to time $t + 1$.">>

The original study used the R programming language and the package TraMineR to execute this algorithm. I didn't find any Python library that implements the algorithm. I did consider, although for a very short time, implementing the algorithm in Python but the package comes with such a nice suite of interpretation and visualization tools that it would be impractical to implement it in the scope of this type of project. So at this point anyone executing the code would have to stop here and continue by executing an R markup file, OMA.Rmd, I wrote as part of this project.

Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering ¶

Data: Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering¶

The final stage in my categorization of Chicago neighborhoods uses the output of the OMA algorithm, which is a distance matrix of all the census blocks sequences. The difference matrix created by TraMineR library in R is saved to disk as an R data type file (typically called an RDS file for the default extension). The data is read back into Python using the pyreadr library, which allows the user to directly import R data structures into Python.

Methodology: Hierarchical Agglomerative Clustering¶

At this point our goal of replicating and updating the original study becomes more complicated due to differences in features in R versus Python libraries. In the study Dr. Delmelle states <<"In this case, a hierarchical Ward’s clustering approach is applied to the data.">> In hierarchical clustering there are different types of metrics the user can choose to minimize when deciding what observations to cluster together. The objective function is where you choose to minimize your metric and in Ward's method the objective function minimizes the total within-cluster variance. This works fine in R using the cluster library and function agnes. In Python the library to use is sklearn (often referred to as scikit-learn) and the method AgglomerativeClustering.

However, scikit-learn will only accept a matrix based on Euclidean distance when using Ward's method. I did try to use the OMA matrix as input and use Ward's method, but that caused the fit() method to display this warning
The symmetric non-negative hollow observation matrix looks suspiciously like an uncondensed distance matrix return linkage(y, method='ward', metric='euclidean')

Nonetheless, as will be seen, just ignoring the warning and continuing produced some credible results. For a dissimilarity matrix only the following objective functions are available in scikit-learn:

  • minimize the maximum distance between observations.
  • minimize the average of the distances between all observations.
  • minimizes the distance between the closest observations of pairs of clusters.

I ran the clustering in R and then all options in Python to compare the Python results with the results in R and the results in the 2010 study. To determine what the right cluster solution might be, took a quite a bit of data analysis, not all of which needs to be repeated in this report (nor the notebook creating this report). However if the reader wants to see more detail about the analysis, including discarded options, please see the notebook NeighborhoodEvolution.ipynb in this project. Here, I will go over on a high level, the steps to determine what were the correct coding options to get credible results.

To start off I did not have to choose the number of clusters. In order to replicate and update the 2010 report, I used 10 clusters as did the original report. Here we have a nice graphic from the original report summarizing the clusters as of 2010 data. They are:

  1. Upgrading from Struggling
  2. Blue Collar to Young Urban
  3. Stable Young Urban
  4. Stable Older Suburban
  5. Stable Older Suburban to Blue Collar
  6. Persistently Struggling
  7. Stable Blue Collar
  8. Blue Collar to Struggling
  9. Newer Suburban to Stable Older Suburban
  10. Newer Suburban

Because I am updating the report with 2019 census data, results will be only close to the 2010 study, but not exact. The R clustering will use the same options as the original report (i.e. distance matrix with Ward's method). It will serve as a point of comparison for Python produced clusters. In other words it will serve as rough baseline for my Python models.

Results ¶

Previous Results¶

First, I need to align my new clusters' categories with categories defined in the 2010 report. The data analysis indicated that three of the original clusters are similar to new clusters where we will find the locations designated for NOF grants in the INVEST South/West RFPs. Below are maps and graphics provided in the 2010 study. At the bottom of the maps is a graphic that gives a good indication on how the clusters were identified.

▮ New Suburban ▮ Old Suburban ▮ Blue Collar ▮ Struggling ▮ Young Urban

Updated Results from R's TraMineR¶

The graphics underneath the maps are generated by the seqIplot function in the R library TraMineR. It shows every transition sequence in that cluster in a matrix of colors. This aids in determining the dominate patterns in each cluster. Using the Python library Matplotlib's pcolormesh graph I was able to recreate this graphic for my own Python clusters, but some of the clusters were varied enough that it was hard to pick out the dominant trend.

However the R Library TraMineR also provided a similar graphic called by the seqrplot function. The difference between the two graphics is that the seqrplot graphic will extract the most common sequences, up to a configurable threshold, and then only display those sequences. This allows the user to concentrate on the dominant trends. The graphic to the right is the visualization of the dominant trends in the clusters I created in R using TraMineR. By using this graphic and the one I recreated in Python, I decided which of my clusters updated with 2019 data fit the classifications defined in the 2010 study, or if they didn't fit any.

Updated Results from Python's scikit-learn¶

Using Matplotlib's pcolormesh graphic in Python I was able to recreate the seqrplot graphic. I found this much more informative than plotting 100% of the sequences. I programmed it so the most frequent sequences would be plotted up till over 25% of the sequences were accounted for. This graphic shows the dominate sequences in the clusters created using Ward's method with AgglomerativeClustering in Python. It did rather well considering that the method does not support the type of input I had and threw the warning mentioned earlier.

Clustering using the objective function that minimizes the distance between the closest observations of pairs of clusters did the worst. It had nine clusters with one data point each, then put all the other data points in one cluster. Using the objective function that minimizes the average of the distances between all observations created a more even distribution of data points than using the closest observations, but it came up with dominant sequences that did not match those we obtained in R, nor that made much sense intuitively for anyone who is familiar with Chicago. Finally I implemented the objective function that minimizes the maximum distance between observations. This worked very well. It produced sequences that lined up well with the baseline and made intuitive sense.

For my R baseline and both Python models, Ward's method and the minimizing maximum distance metrics, my clusters lined up, matching the sequence patterns of the 2010 clusters 9 out of 10 times, with each new model missing one of the original patterns, but each new model missing a different pattern from the others. Preferring the Python Ward's method model would be a rather dubious choice given that it does not officially support the input we fed it for the objective function it uses. Nonetheless, at first glance it seems to perform well, and curiosity got the best of me at this point. I decided to compare them further. Using the R model as our baseline I decided to compare the Python models to it using Jaccard similarity. The Jaccard index is used to compare two sets. It divides the number of data points in common in the two sets (the intersection) by the number of all the unique data points of both sets (the union), thus 1 is everything in common and 0 is nothing in common. I did this for each aligning cluster and the overall data sets.

This table shows how each cluster aligns and its Jaccard index compared to the new R model.

			The similarity of Ward's Method model to the R baseline has a Jaccard score of 0.53
			The similarity of the maximum distance model to R baseline has a Jaccard score of 0.634

So overall the model using maximum distance seems to be the most appropriate.

Discussion and Conclusions ¶

Now I'm ready to return to the original question. INVEST South/West is about to award millions of dollars in grants to certain RFP locations, in part due to Dr. Delmelle's study that used data from 1970 ending in 2010. Given that I have updated this process with the latest census data available from 2019, can the original conclusions be confirmed? First, it's necessary to take a look at how each of the models has classified the census tracts that contain the points of interest.

Most of the census blocks are classified as economically struggling, but some are stable blue collar. Let's zoom in using some visualization and see if this can provide any more clarity. Note that the RFP locations can have three statuses: Awarded, Reviewing and Soliciting. RFPs that have been awarded are in green, those that are being reviewed are in yellow, and those that are still being solicited are red.

Conclusion ¶

With the help of maps it can be seen that most of the NOF RFP sites are in persistently economically disadvantaged neighborhoods, while those that are not technically classified as such by my models, are either on the border of an economically disadvantaged tract or in the case of the northern most sites, very close to disadvantaged neighborhoods. So even in the latter case the update confirms the original conclusions that the neediest parts of the city would benefit directly or indirectly by some very close spillover from the economic incentives being offered the by the Neighborhood Opportunity Funds, even when updated with 2019 data.

These data science techniques present some extra challenges. Many statistical methods will give the same results with the same data, always. Many unsupervised learning algorithms in data science, such as K-means, can be dependent on initial values that can be somewhat random. This can complicate the ability to replicate studies, and since K-means was the first step in series of affected downstream processes, replicatable results could not be guaranteed exactly, only approximately. However, this could be mitigated by setting a random_state number (seed in R) and publishing it with the results.

Conclusion Epilogue¶

I did consider whether it would be practical to do a retail gap analysis on any of the sites in question but decided against in for two reasons. First, conducting a through and useful investigation of this sort takes additional data containing revenue information of each retail sector, which is much more than a user can get from Foursquare, or for free. There are good datasets available for purchase with this information, which could be worthwhile to an organization about to award millions of dollars in investment grants, but that is beyond the means of an online course. Second, some of the RFPs mentioned the conditions about how the grants could be used, and they did have input from retail gap analysis studies, but this was always secondary to the survey data and input from local community groups.

Now, those of us who are data-driven might be inclined to prefer hard revenue figures over opinions, but local input actually makes a lot of sense. A gap analysis might reveal that an economically disadvantaged neighborhood may have a huge shortage of overpriced coffee shops and used-clothing stores with the word "Vintage" in the title compared to a Young Urban (i.e. gentrified) neighborhood. But if the residents of the former neighborhood opine that closing this gap would not improve the quality of their lives, I would be inclined to believe them.
